{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Mass",
      "simpleDefinition": "The amount of matter in an object, measured in kilograms (kg). It stays the same regardless of location.",
      "anchor": "Think of a 50kg bag of plaster; its mass is the same whether it is on the ground or on a roof.",
      "misconception": "Often confused with weight, but mass does not change with gravity."
    },
    {
      "term": "Weight",
      "simpleDefinition": "The force exerted on an object by gravity, measured in Newtons (N).",
      "anchor": "Calculated by multiplying mass by gravity (9.81).",
      "misconception": "In everyday talk, people say weight is in kg, but in science, weight is a force in Newtons."
    },
    {
      "term": "Gravity (g)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The constant acceleration that pulls objects toward Earth, valued at 9.81m/s².",
      "anchor": "The 'multiplier' used to turn mass (kg) into weight (N).",
      "misconception": "Assuming gravity is exactly 10; for C&G 2365, always use 9.81."
    },
    {
      "term": "Fulcrum",
      "simpleDefinition": "The pivot point around which a lever turns.",
      "anchor": "The center pin of a pair of side cutters.",
      "misconception": "Believing the pivot must always be in the exact center of the tool."
    },
    {
      "term": "Class I Lever",
      "simpleDefinition": "A lever where the fulcrum (pivot) is positioned between the effort and the load.",
      "anchor": "A pair of pliers or a seesaw.",
      "misconception": "Thinking all levers are Class I because they are the most common."
    },
    {
      "term": "Class II Lever",
      "simpleDefinition": "A lever where the load is positioned between the fulcrum and the effort.",
      "anchor": "A wheelbarrow or a conduit bender.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the load position with the effort position."
    },
    {
      "term": "Class III Lever",
      "simpleDefinition": "A lever where the effort is applied between the fulcrum and the load.",
      "anchor": "A pair of tweezers or a person's arm lifting a weight.",
      "misconception": "Assuming these levers make the load feel lighter; they actually trade force for precision or distance."
    },
    {
      "term": "Mechanical Advantage",
      "simpleDefinition": "The trade-off where a machine allows you to move a large load using less effort.",
      "anchor": "Using a long-handled conduit bender to bend steel pipe easily.",
      "misconception": "Thinking machines 'create' energy; they simply redirect or multiply force."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Mass is the 'stuff', Weight is the 'pull'.",
    "Weight (N) = Mass (kg) x 9.81.",
    "Class I: Pivot in the middle.",
    "Class II: Load in the middle.",
    "Class III: Effort in the middle."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using kilograms to describe weight in a technical calculation.",
    "Misidentifying the lever class of common electrical hand tools.",
    "Forgetting to use the 9.81 constant when calculating force on a fixing."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "202-3a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Mass vs Weight",
      "objective": "Differentiate between mass and weight using correct units and the constant of gravity.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the electrical trade, you must distinguish between mass and weight to ensure fixings and containment systems are safe. Mass is the actual amount of matter in an object, measured in kilograms (kg). Whether a motor is on your workbench or being hoisted to a roof, its mass remains the same because the 'stuff' it is made of hasn't changed.",
        "Weight, however, is a force. It is the result of gravity pulling on that mass. In technical terms, weight is measured in Newtons (N). To find the weight of an object, you multiply its mass by the acceleration due to gravity. For your C&G 2365 studies, always use the constant of 9.81 m/s² for gravity.",
        "For example, if a cable drum has a mass of 100kg, its weight is 981N (100kg x 9.81). Using kilograms to describe weight is a common mistake in everyday speech, but as an electrician, you must use Newtons when calculating the downward force equipment exerts on a bracket, tray, or ceiling fixing."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember: Mass is the 'stuff' in kg; Weight is the 'pull' in Newtons. Always multiply by 9.81."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-3a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Mechanical Systems",
      "objective": "Identify the three classes of levers and the basic function of gears and pulleys.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Mechanical systems like levers, gears, and pulleys allow us to move heavy loads with less effort—a concept known as mechanical advantage. Levers are categorized into three classes based on the position of the fulcrum (the pivot point), the effort (the force you apply), and the load (the object being moved).",
        "In a Class I lever, the fulcrum is positioned between the effort and the load, like a pair of side cutters or pliers. A Class II lever places the load in the middle, between the fulcrum and the effort. A common trade example is a conduit bender or a wheelbarrow; this layout is specifically designed to make heavy lifting or bending easier. In a Class III lever, the effort is applied in the middle, such as when using tweezers or your own arm to lift a tool.",
        "Beyond levers, gears and pulleys are essential for mechanical advantage. Gears can trade speed for torque, allowing a motor to turn a heavy load. Pulleys redirect force and, when used in sets, reduce the effort required to lift heavy equipment like large cable reels into position."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about what is in the middle: Class I is the Pivot, Class II is the Load, and Class III is the Effort."
    }
  ]
}

